{"parse":{"title":"moon","pageid":4403,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Moon|mo-on|mòòn|Möön}}\n\n==English==\n[[Image:Jeff_Fennell_-_Early_Morning_Moon_%28by%29.jpg|thumb|The Moon (waning crescent).]]\n[[Image:FullMoonHauknes.jpg|thumb|right|The Moon (full).]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|moone||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:mone<id:moon>|tree=1}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*meh₁-}}{{word|en|ine|mḗh₁n̥s}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|mon}}, {{m|enm|mona}}, {{m|enm|mone}}, {{m|enm|monæ}}, {{m|enm|moone}}, {{m|enm|moyn}}, {{m|enm|moyne}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mōna|t=moon}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*mānō}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*mēnô|t=moon}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*mḗh₁n̥s|t=moon; month}}, probably from {{m|ine-pro|*meh₁-|t=to measure}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|muin}}, {{m|sco|mune|t=moon}}, {{cog|yol|mona}}, {{m|yol|moone|t=moon}}, {{cog|frr|moune}}, {{m|frr|muun|t=moon}}, {{cog|stq|Moune|t=moon}}, {{cog|fy|moanne|t=moon}}, {{cog|gsw|Maan}}, {{m|gsw|manä}}, {{m|gsw|manòd}}, {{m|gsw|mànund}}, {{m|gsw|meini}}, {{m|gsw|moanu}}, {{m|gsw|Mond|t=moon}}, {{cog|bar|mone|t=moon}}, {{cog|gmw-cfr|Mond|t=moon}}, {{cog|cim|ma}}, {{m|cim|maano}}, {{m|cim|må|t=moon}}, {{cog|nl|maan}}, {{m|nl|maen|t=moon}}, {{cog|de|Mond|t=moon}}, {{cog|li|maon}}, {{m|li|maond}}, {{m|li|moan}}, {{m|li|mond}}, {{m|li|Moën}}, {{m|li|Mǫnt}}, {{m|li|Mǫe̩nt}}, {{m|li|Mǫǫnt|t=moon}}, {{cog|lb|Mound|t=moon}}, {{cog|mhn|mu'|t=moon}}, {{cog|wym|mönd}}, {{m|wym|mönt|t=moon}}, {{cog|vls|moane|t=moon}}, {{cog|yi|מאָנט|t=moon}}, {{cog|da,nb,nn,sv|måne|t=moon}}, {{cog|fo,is|máni|t=moon}}, {{cog|nrn|måni|t=moon}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|mine|t=moon}}, {{cog|got|𐌼𐌴𐌽𐌰|t=the Moon}}; also {{cog|kw,cy|mis|t=month}}, {{cog|ga|mí|t=month}}, {{cog|gv|mee|t=month}}, {{cog|gd|mìos|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|la|mēnsis|t=month}}, {{cog|xum|𐌌𐌄𐌍𐌆𐌍𐌄|t=Moon}}, {{cog|el|μήνας|t=month}}, {{cog|sq|muaj|t=month}}, {{cog|lv|mēnesis|t=month}}, {{m|lv|mēness|t=moon}}, {{cog|lt|mėnuo|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|be,ru|ме́сяц|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|bg,mk|ме́сец|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|cs|měsíc|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|pl|miesiąc}}, {{m|pl|mięsiąc}}, {{m|pl|mniesiąc}}, {{m|pl|niesiąc|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|sh|ме̏се̄ц}}, {{m|sh|мје̏се̄ц}}, {{m|sh|mȅsēc}}, {{m|sh|mjȅsēc|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|sk|mesiac|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|sl|mesec|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|uk|мі́сяць|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|hy|ամիս|t=month}}, {{cog|ae|𐬨𐬃𐬢𐬵|t=month}}, {{m|ae|𐬨𐬂𐬢𐬵𐬀|t=moon}}, {{cog|xbc|μαο}}, {{m|xbc|μαυο|t=month}}, {{cog|ckb,sdh|مانگ|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|kmr|meh|t=month}}, {{cog|os|мӕй|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|ps|مياشت|tr=myâšt|t=month}}, {{cog|fa|مه|tr=mah}}, {{m|fa|ماه|tr=māh / mâh|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|tg|моҳ|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|xto|mañ|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|txb|meñe|t=moon; month}}, {{cog|sa|मस्}}, {{m|sa|मास्|t=moon; month}}. See also {{m|en|month}}, a related term within Indo-European.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\nThe usage of \"moon\" to refer to the act reflected its use as a metaphor for the buttocks since 1743. It was popularised from American student slang in the 1960s.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/muːn/|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-moon.ogg|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-moon.wav|a=RP}}\n* {{IPA|en|/mun/|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-moon.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-moon.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/mʉn/|a=Scotland,NI}}\n* {{rhymes|en|uːn|s=1}}\n\n===Proper noun===\n{{en-proper-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q405}} {{lb|en|with \"the\"|singulare tantum}} {{alternative case form of|en|Moon|gloss=the [[Earth]]'s only permanent natural [[satellite]]}}.\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|book=Matthew|chapter=24|verse=29|folio=xxxiiij|verso=yes|passage=Immediatly after the tribulacions off thoſe dayes / ſhall the ſun be derkeneth: and the '''mone''' ſhall not geve her light / and the ſtarrꝭ ſhall fall from heven / and the powers of hevẽ ſhall move}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1886|translator=H.L. Br&aelig;kstad|author=w:Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|title=Folk and Fairy Tales|page=233|passage=\"I suppose I may have leave to do that!\" Yes, she could do that, he said, but there was no road to that place; it lay east of the sun and west of the '''moon''', and she could never find her way there.}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q2537}}{{lb|en|informal|by extension of {{l|en|Moon}}}} Any natural satellite of a {{l|en|planet}}.\n#: {{ux|en|The stargazer observed the '''moons''' of Jupiter for over a year.}}\n#: {{ux|en|That's no '''moon''', you idiot... it's a space station!}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Anton Troianovski|title=Hunting Ghost Particles Beneath the World’s Deepest Lake|magazine=w:The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/30/science/neutrinos-lake-baikal.html|date=2021-03-30|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330070419/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/30/science/neutrinos-lake-baikal.html|archivedate=2021-03-30\n|passage=The field’s practitioners believe that as they learn to read the universe using neutrinos, they could make new, unexpected discoveries — much as the lensmakers who first developed the telescope could not have imagined that Galileo would later use it to discover the '''moons''' of Jupiter.}}\n# {{lb|en|literary}} A {{l|en|[[month]], particularly a [[lunar month]]}}.\n#: {{ux|en|They stayed with their aunt and uncle for many '''moons'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1603|author=William Shakespeare|title=Othello\n|passage=For since these arms of mine had seven years' pith,<br/>Till now some nine '''moons''' wasted, they have used<br/>Their dearest action in the tented field…}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1737|author=John Brickell|title=The natural history of North-Carolina|page=308–309\n|passage=They number their age by '''Moons''' or Winters, and say a Woman or a Man is so many '''Moons''' old, and so they do with all memorable Actions in life, accounting it to be so many '''Moons''' or Winters since such or such a thing happened.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1822|author=Thomas Love Peacock|title=Maid Marian|page=238\n|passage=Many '''moons''' had waxed and waned when on the afternoon of a lovely summer day a lusty broad-boned knight was riding through the forest of Sherwood.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|author={{w|Edgar Rice Burroughs}}|title={{w|The Return of Tarzan}}|publisher=Ballantine Books|location=New York|year_published=1963|page=128|passage=“From whence came the yellow metal, Busuli?” he asked. The black pointed toward the southeast. “A '''moon’s''' march away—maybe more,” he replied.}}\n#* '''2002''', Russell Allen, \"Incantations of the Apprentice\", on Symphony X, ''The Odyssey''.\n#*: {{quote|en|Through eerie reach of ancient woods / Where lumbering mists arise / I journey for nines '''moons''' of the year / To where a land of legend lies}}\n# A representation of the moon, usually as a crescent or as a circle with a face; a crescent-shaped shape, symbol, or object.\n#: {{ux|en|The wizard costume was decorated with stars and '''moons'''.}}\n# A {{l|en|[[crescent]]-like [[outwork]] in a [[fortification]]}}.\n#: {{ux|en|The '''moons''' surrounding the city walls were built in the sixteenth century.}}\n# The eighteenth [[trump]]/[[major arcana]] card of the [[tarot]].\n# {{lb|en|cartomancy}} The thirty-second {{l|en|Lenormand}} card.\n# {{lb|en|card games}} In [[hearts]], the action of taking all the point cards in one hand.\n\n====Usage notes====\n* Used attributively in a variety of collocations and compounds to indicate something foreign or difficult to understand: ''[[moon language]]'', ''[[moonspeak]]'', ''[[moon runes]]'', ''[[moon logic]]'', etc.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|Earth's sole natural satellite}} {{l|en|Moon}}\n* {{sense|natural satellite of a planet}} {{l|en|satellite}}\n* {{sense|month}} {{l|en|calendar month}}, {{l|en|lunar month}}, {{l|en|month}}\n* [[☽]], [[☾]]\n* See also [[Thesaurus:moon]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|antimoon\n|ask for the moon\n|barley moon\n|beaver moon\n|black moon\n|blood moon\n|blue moon\n|bomber's moon\n|buck moon|moon jump|moon snake\n|cold moon|finger pointing at the moon\n|corn moon\n|corn planting moon| moon ring\n|crescent moon\n|crow moon\n|dark moon\n|deer moon\n|egg moon\n|exomoon|moon deity|moon jellyfish\n|fingernail moon|moon joy\n|fish moon\n|flower moon|moon goddess\n|frost moon\n|frosty moon\n|fruit moon\n|full moon\n|Galilean moon\n|gibbous moon\n|go howl at the moon\n|grain moon\n|grass moon\n|growing moon\n|gypsy moon\n|half moon\n|half-moon\n|hang the moon\n|hare moon\n|harvest moon\n|hay moon\n|honeymoon\n|honey moon\n|howl at the moon\n|hunger moon\n|hunter's moon\n|ice moon\n|know someone from the man in the moon\n|know someone from the man on the moon\n|long night moon\n|moonbound\n|man in the moon\n|man on the moon\n|many moons ago\n|mead moon\n|micromoon\n|midsummer moon\n|milk moon\n|mini-moon\n|minimoon,mini-moon\n|mock moon\n|moon bag\n|moonball\n|moon base\n|moonbat\n|moonbath\n|moonbathe\n|moonbeam\n|moon beam\n|moon-beam\n|moonbear\n|moon bear\n|moon-bill\n|moonbird\n|moon-blind,moonblind,moon blind\n|moon blindness\n|moonblink\n|moon block\n|moonblood\n|moon boot\n|moon bounce,moonbounce\n|moonbow\n|moon buggy\n|moonburn\n|moon-cake\n|mooncake,moon cake\n|mooncalf\n|moon-calf\n|moon carrot\n|moonchild,moon-child,moon child\n|moonclad\n|mooncraft\n|mooncrete\n|moon cricket\n|mooncup\n|mooncusser\n|moon cycle\n|moon daisy\n|moondial\n|moon dog\n|moondown\n|moondrome\n|moondust\n|mooner\n|moonery\n|moonet\n|moonette\n|mooney\n|moon-eyed\n|mooneye,moon-eye,moon eye\n|moon-face\n|moon face\n|moon-faced\n|moon facies\n|moonfall\n|moonfish\n|moon flask\n|moon-flask\n|moonflask\n|moonflight\n|moonflower\n|moonful\n|moon garden\n|moongate\n|moon gate\n|moongazer\n|moongazing\n|moonglade\n|moonglow\n|moon god\n|moon guitar\n|moonhood\n|moonie\n|moon illusion\n|mooning\n|moonish\n|moonito\n|moon jelly\n|moon-knife\n|moon landing\n|moon language\n|moonless,moon-less\n|moonlet\n|moon letter\n|moonlight,moon-light\n|moonlike\n|moon-lily\n|moonling\n|moonlit,moon-lit\n|moonlitten\n|moon logic\n|moonly\n|moon madness\n|moon-man\n|moonman\n|moonmilk\n|moon milk\n|moon month\n|moonmoon,moon-moon,moon moon\n|moon moth\n|moonnaut\n|moon on a stick\n|moonpath\n|moonphase\n|moon pie\n|moon pigeon\n|moon-pool\n|moon pool,moonpool\n|moonport\n|moonquake,moon-quake\n|moonraker\n|moonraking\n|moonrat\n|moon rat\n|moonrise,moon-rise,moon rise\n|moon rock\n|moon rocket\n|moon rocks\n|moonroof\n|moon roof\n|moon rune\n|moonrunes\n|moonsail\n|moonsault\n|moonscape\n|moonscreen\n|moonseed\n|moonset,moon-set,moon set\n|moonshine,moon-shine\n|moonship\n|moon shot,moon-shot,moonshot\n|moonsickle\n|moon-sickle\n|moon sickle\n|moon sign\n|moon snail\n|moon soup\n|moonspeak,moon-speak\n|moonstomp\n|moonstone\n|moonstricken\n|moonstruck\n|moontime\n|moon tower\n|moon trefoil\n|moon unit\n|moonup\n|moonwake\n|moonwalk\n|moonward\n|moonwashed\n|moonwatcher\n|moonwise\n|moonwort\n|moony\n|moon zither\n|Mountains of the Moon\n|new moon\n|old moon\n|once in a blue moon\n|once in a purple moon\n|over the moon\n|phase of the moon\n|pink moon\n|planting moon\n|ploonet\n|promise the moon\n|quarter moon\n|quasimoon,quasi-moon\n|quaternary moon\n|rain moon\n|reach for the moon\n|rising of the moon\n|rose moon\n|sap moon\n|see the dark side of the moon\n|shepherd moon\n|shoot for the moon\n|shoot the moon\n|sickle moon\n|sliver moon\n|smuggler's moon\n|snow moon\n|storm moon\n|strawberry moon\n|sturgeon moon\n|sub-moon\n|submoon,sub-moon\n|sugaring moon\n|super moon\n|supermoon,super-moon\n|the moon on a stick\n|think one hung the moon\n|thumbnail moon\n|thunder moon\n|to the moon\n|to the moon and back\n|Trojan moon\n|waning moon\n|waxing moon\n|wind moon\n|winter moon\n|wolf moon\n|worm moon\n|young moon\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|ja|ムーン|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|srn|mun}}\n* {{desc|tpi|mun}}\n* {{desc|tcs|mun}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial}} To display one's [[buttock]]s to, typically as a [[jest]], [[insult]], or [[protest]].\n#: {{cot|en|flash|streak}}\n#: {{ux|en|The hooligans '''mooned''' the riot police.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It was ill-advised of Sam to '''moon''' the photographer during the shoot.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial}} To [[gaze]] at [[lovingly]] or in [[adoration]].\n#* {{RQ:Lindsay Age of Consent|year=1962|page=164|passage=Bradly stood bewitched, '''mooning''' at the moon. Betimes he bent in a grotesque posture and looked at it between his legs, which was to rid his mind of preconceived colour values by seeing them upside down.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial}} (''usually followed by'' '''over''' ''or'' '''after''') To [[fuss]] over something [[adoringly]]; to be [[infatuate]]d with someone.\n#: {{ux|en|Sarah '''mooned''' over Sam's photograph for months.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You've been '''mooning''' after her forever; why not just ask her out?}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=January 12, 2017|author=Jesse Hassenger| title=A literal monster truck is far from the stupidest thing about Monster Trucks| work=The Onion AV Club| url=http://www.avclub.com/review/literal-monster-truck-far-stupidest-thing-about-mo-248111| passage=On some level, the filmmakers behind Monster Trucks must have recognized the ill fit of Till playing a teenager, because they cast Jane Levy, a 27-year-old who can pass for younger but not a decade younger, as Meredith, a nerdy classmate of Tripp’s who '''moons''' over him as she insists on making an appointment to tutor him in biology.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|author=HarryBlank|work=w:SCP Foundation|title=Working Wonders|date=24 September 2023|url=https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/26-working-wonders|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240525140823/https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/26-working-wonders|archivedate=25 May 2024|accessdate=25 May 2024|text=<p>\"No, you're right.\" Udo shook this newest distraction out of her head. She knew it would come creeping back in through the ears in due time, just as she knew the best way to dispel it was to finish the job and link up with the rest of the Site. In any event, there was something in what Brenda had said that didn't make sense... \"But why would he be '''mooning''' over her, if she's still awake?\"</p><p>\"Because he's with V—\"</p><p>\"Veiksaar!\" Udo fairly shouted, slapping her forehead. \"Oh, shit. This is going to take a lot of getting used to.\"</p>}}\n# To [[spend time]] [[idly]], [[absent-mindedly]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1898|author=Joseph Conrad|title=[[s:Youth (Conrad)|Youth]]|passage=We were only three on board. The poor old skipper '''mooned''' in the cabin.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2001|author=Stephen King|title=w:[[The Death of Jack Hamilton]]|passage=I '''mooned''' around. I was mighty sick of the room by then.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To expose to the rays of the Moon.\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[adorn]] with moons or [[crescent]]s.\n# {{lb|en|cryptocurrency|of a coin or token}} To [[rise]] in price rapidly or suddenly. (from [[to the moon]])\n#: {{ux|en|It is impractical if a currency '''moons''' and plummets often.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Mark Grabowski|title=Cryptocurrencies: A Primer on Digital Money|year=2019|publisher=Routledge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0KeaDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT74&dq=%22mooned%22+bitcoin&hl=&cd=5&source=gbs_api#v=onepage&q=%22mooned%22%20bitcoin&f=false|isbn=978-0-429-51357-2|passage=I've followed several of the most popular crypto pundits on Twitter and discovered they constantly brag about their one big Hail Mary pick that '''mooned''' but neglect to mention – or delete – their numerous fumbles.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|author=Trey Parker|authorlink=Trey Parker|actor={{w|Trey Parker}}|role=Fire Chief|episode={{w|South Park: Post COVID: The Return of COVID}}|title={{w|South Park}}|url=https://www.paramountplus.com/movies/south-park-post-covid-the-return-of-covid/Wnj6RyDK_sWCjm81KIBBZOk_PwsfWnii|date=December 16, 2021|time=29:23|text=“It was like nothing I ever saw. Just complete murder and carnage.” “Everything seemed calm at first but then this guy in a suit shows up talking about investment opportunities. Next thing you know these people over here started chanting, \"Hoddle, Hoddle,\" and their NFTs started '''mooning'''. And then, these guys over here started saying those guys right there right-clicked 'em and-and called for a pump-and-dump, which made these guys beat the living hell out of anyone who said it was just FOMO and died screaming that is was the flippening. Luckily I came out of it ok. I got this little miniature donkey with a lit-up sombrero.” “Did you see where the guy in the suit went afterwards?” “Nah, he just waltzed right away like nothin' happened.” “Chief, you better come take a look at this. We got a small turtle with wings, could be a great investment opportunity.” “Excuse me, gentlemen.”}}\n# {{lb|en|card games}} To [[shoot the moon]].\n\n====Translations====\n{{see translation subpage|Verb}}\n\n===Related terms===\n* {{l|en|month}}<!--has a related etymology-->\n* {{l|en|moonsick}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|lunar}}\n* {{l|en|Moonie}}<!--etymologically unrelated-->\n* {{l|en|Selene}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{wp|<dab>}}\n* {{pedia|moon}}\n* {{pedia|natural satellite}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=mnoo|Mono|OMON|mono|mono-|nomo-}}\n\n{{C|en|Buttocks|Light sources|Moons|Moon}}\n\n==Bavarian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|bar|mon|mònn}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|bar|gmh|man}}, from {{inh|bar|goh|man}}, from {{inh|bar|gem-pro|*mann-}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|Mann}}, {{cog|nl|man}}, {{cog|en|man}}, {{cog|is|maður}}, {{cog|sv|man}}, {{cog|got|𐌼𐌰𐌽𐌽𐌰}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|bar|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|bar|Timau}} [[man]]\n# {{lb|bar|Timau}} [[husband]]\n\n===References===\n*{{R:Patuzzi}}\n\n{{topics|bar|People|Family|Male}}\n\n==Chinese==\n\n===Etymology===\nDeliberate misspelling of {{m|zh|mon}}. Originated from a post on {{w|HKGolden}} circa 2005.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{zh-pron\n|c=mun1\n|cat=n,v\n}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|zh|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese|Internet slang|neologism}} {{synonym of|zh|mon}} {{zh-mw|c:隻}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{zh-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese|Internet slang|neologism}} {{synonym of|zh|mon}}\n\n==Cornish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|kw|cnx|mon}}, from {{inh|kw|oco|muin}}, from {{inh|kw|cel-bry-pro|*muɨn||mild, gentle}}, from {{inh|kw|cel-pro|*meinos||tender, soft}}. Cognate with {{cog|br|moan}} and {{cog|cy|mwyn||mild, gentle}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{kw-adj|am}}\n\n# {{l|en|slender}}, {{l|en|slim}}, {{l|en|thin}}\n#: {{syn|kw|tanow}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|kw|cel-bry-pro|*muɨn||ore, metal}}, from {{inh|kw|cel-pro|*meinis||ore, metal}}. Cognate with {{cog|en|mine}} (via {{cog|cel-gau|-}} and {{cog|fro|-}}), {{cog|ga|mian||ore}}, and {{cog|cy|mwyn||ore, mineral}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{kw-noun|m|monyon}}\n\n# {{l|en|mineral}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{kw-mut}}\n\n==Finnish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fi-pronunciation}}\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|fi|contraction}}\n\n# {{lb|fi|dialectal|Southern Ostrobothnian}} {{contraction of|fi|mä|oon|lit=I'm}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|fi|a=mnoo|mono|mono-}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|frr|maan||Föhr-Amrum}}\n* {{alt|frr|Man||Sylt}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|frr|ofs|man}}, from {{inh|frr|gmw-pro|*mann}}, from {{inh|frr|gem-pro|*mann-}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|frr|[mʊn]|a=Mooring}} <!--irregular-->\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|frr|noun|g=m|plural|[[mååns]] </b>''or'' {{q|after numerals}}<b> [[moon]]}} {{tlb|frr|Mooring}}\n\n# {{l|en|man}} {{gloss|adult male human}}\n# {{l|en|husband}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* For the plural, {{m|frr|kjarl|kjarls}} is often preferred; see there.\n\n{{topic|frr|Human}}\n\n==Teop==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tio|noun}}\n\n# [[woman]]\n\n===References===\n* Ulrike Mosel, ''[http://www.smg.surrey.ac.uk/media/1147/teop_sketch_grammar_may07.pdf#page=51 The Teop sketch grammar]''"}}